      <title>Re: EverQuest and EverQuest 2 Connectivity</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Lore&amp;message.id=11618#M11618</link>
      <description>I'm coming from an almost entirely EQ2 background, played EQ for a while but never got into the lore. EQ2 is a phenomenal game but I basically maxed out my character and there's not much else I could be doing at the moment, so I've come over here for the progression server. The EQ2 lore boards actually have quite a lot of discussion on this point, most of it with a number of broken record trolls that can't understand the possibility of some tie-ins between the game. But a popular topic, for instance, was if MM was a god in the EQ2 world.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Researching that, I actually dug up an early beta post by one of the main EQ2 devs saying that they had consulted extensively with the current EQ devs and that there was no lore divergence up until the next couple expansions at least (at that point it would've covered up until OoW, I think). Of course this is sort of backwards from the question you're asking (EQ2 lore in EQ1), so here's my take on different kinds of lore:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Note: "the past" refers to before the divergence, "the future" refers to afterward&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;EQ2 spoilers ahoy!&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;1. Things directly influenced by the rending/shattering exist in EQ2, but not in EQ1.&lt;br&gt;Ex: Because of the cataclysmic events, Nagafen and Vox are freed and pop out a big pile of prismatic eggs. This obviously does not happen in the EQ1 timeline.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;2. People and places that exist in "the future" in one game, and could exist in the other, exist in both games until contradicted.&lt;br&gt;Ex: Darathar is a dragon that to my knowledge does not exist in EQ1 lore. His factional allegiances are a bit questionable and he doesn't seem to have been a major player in the dragon world before. He assumes a human guise to manipulate mortals and uses a tool called the Harness to martial forces of drakota to attack Nagafen and Vox, presumably over their stockpile of prismatic eggs. Do the Harness or Darathar exist in EQ1? It's not something you'll want to be building elaborate theories off of, but sure, why not?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;3. Events that happen in "the future" in both games are a question mark until they're confirmed one way or the other.&lt;br&gt;Ex: MM's godhood is a big question mark in EQ2. No confirmation one way or the other, so it's silly to say definitively that it happened or didn't happen.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;4. Events that happen in "the past" but were referenced first in "the future" exist in both games until contradicted.&lt;br&gt;Vhalen is responsible for a lot of the lore in EQ2. Aside from being awesome at his job, he claims to have tomes and tomes of information that he draws lore from which predate even the existence of EQ2. Unless the devs make a boo-boo, things that are referenced to exist in the past probably exist in the past in both games, even if they weren't brought to light until a current expansion.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Ex: In EQ2 one of the more interesting plotlines that pervades in the background of the game is the shadowed men invasion of Norrath. There are a series of books that describe the shadowed men as interplanetary, transdimensional bringers of darkness. Their plot has been hatching on Norrath for a while, but they haven't struck yet, though they have advanced their plans by the time EQ2 rolls around. They are also tied in with the creation of Bertoxxulous, or at least the fall of the Xulous. Unless there's something in EQ1 which contradicts this (which I'd like to know actually, as it's my favorite lore subject :D) then it probably is true in EQ1 as well.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;5. Things that are clearly directly contradictory are true as per the game.&lt;br&gt;Ex: I can't think of any right now, but a couple were posted above.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;6. Zone layouts are up for grabs as per artistic license.&lt;br&gt;It's just too hard, given the "approximate" nature of the representation of zones in both games and the amount of unexplored territory, to really get a handle on this. I mean, look at the difference between Nek 2.0 and Nek 1.0, and those were actually supposed to cover the same territory with no catastrophic changes. Same with Freeport 1.0 to Freeport 2.0.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Of course, any of this is subject to change at any time at the whim of the devs. History has shown that even trusted, confirmed lore sources are sometimes self-contradictory. What it basically amounts to is that this discussion is fun, but really doesn't mean jack... the devs will do as they see fit and we'll be left trying to string the lore together :P&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
