      <description>&lt;div&gt;actually retconned can be done by the creators to.  In Star Trek, the guy(I think it was Cochran) who invented faster than light travel for Earth had his age changed from when he invented the warp drive(and maybe his birthdate).  In the original episodes it he was in his late fifties, yet in First Contact, he was in his thirties.  Another point of interest, &amp;quot;Splinter of the Mind's Eye&amp;quot; was orginally going to be the canon story after &amp;quot;A New Hope&amp;quot;, if &amp;quot;A New Hope&amp;quot; did not do well.  And here is the definiton of ret con from dictionary.com&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;retcon&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;/ret'kon/ retroactive continuity&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The common situation in fiction where a new story &amp;quot;reveals&amp;quot;&lt;br&gt;things about events in previous stories, usually leaving the&lt;br&gt;&amp;quot;facts&amp;quot; the same (thus preserving continuity) while completely&lt;br&gt;changing their interpretation. For example, revealing that a&lt;br&gt;whole season of &amp;quot;Dallas&amp;quot; was a dream was a retcon.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;P.S. I swear I'm not a sci-fi nerd&lt;/div&gt;</description>
