      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;My stance is that if it is contradictory to whatever game that you are playing then said lore is not applicable.&amp;nbsp; If there is nothing that contradicts it in the game you are playing, then there is nothing wrong with considering it as a way to fill in some of the lore gaps in the games.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Discrepancies can also be explained from a RP perspective as being that the dating used by those who study history in EQ2 could be off some number of years that might put it outside of EQLive's time frame.&amp;nbsp; Or they could have just simply have the wrong information due to misinterpretation of descriptions of what happened or misinformation spread to re-write what happened.&amp;nbsp; Personally I don't see anything wrong with someone using lore from another EQ game to &lt;STRONG&gt;further&lt;/STRONG&gt; support a view&amp;nbsp;about EQ1 they hold&amp;nbsp;as long as that lore isn't contradicted by something in EQ Live.&amp;nbsp; I also don't see any problem with someone using non-contradictory lore to fill in gaps in EQ history, but if something&amp;nbsp;is introduced&amp;nbsp;ingame via an expansion or other&amp;nbsp;serverwide shared event&amp;nbsp;and "proves"&amp;nbsp;that history&amp;nbsp;to be false then they are out of luck.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
